s of political relations among indigenous Muslim rulers, their subjects, and external powers seeking the subjugation of Philippine Muslims. He also explores the motivations of the ordinary men and women who fight in armed separatist struggles and investigates the formation of nationalist identities. A skillful meld of historical detail and ethnographic research, Muslim Rulers and Rebels makes a compelling contribution to the study of protest, rebellion, and revolution worldwide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMuslimsxPhilippinesxCotabato City Region. 0aMuslimsxPolitical activityzCotabato City RegionzPhilippines. 0aMuslimsxPolitics and governmentxPhilippinesxMindanao Island. 0aMuslimszPhilippineszCotabato City Region. 0aMuslimszPhilippineszMindanao IslandxPolitics and government. 0aMuslimszPhilippineszMindanao Island. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  acomparative politics.  acomparative studies on muslim societies.  acultural studies.  aculture and power.  aethnography.  aethnoreligious political movements.  aindigenous muslim rulers.  aislam.  ajabidah massacre.  amindanao independence movement.  amuslim independence movement.  amuslim separatism.  amuslim separatist rebellion.  anationalism.  anationalist identity.  aphilippine muslims.  aphilippines history.  apolitical organization.  apolitical relations.  aprotest.  arebellion.  areligion.  arevolution.  asocial history.  athe philippines.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021016540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091964840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520919648423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520919648/o